See Also
Leprosy - Papua New Guinea (Bougainville) 980115004946
Leprosy - Papua New Guinea (Bougainville) (02) 980116002908
[1
Date: Thu, 15 Jan 1998 07:45:19 -1000
From: Dr. Richard Frankel <rfrankel@hawaii.edu>

The treatment for leprosy includes dapsone but MUST include other drugs.
In most countries, a regimen proposed by WHO and called MDT (Multiple Drug
Therapy) is used with great success. This is so for both Solomon Islands
and Papua New Guinea. Dapsone should not be used alone. It is used with
one or two other drugs, depending upon the type of leprosy. MDT has been
very successful in reducing the prevalence of leprosy, though it has not
had much effect on the incidence. It is not clear that BCG has had any
impact on the epidemiology of leprosy.
While I have worked in both Solomon Islands and Papua New Guinea, I have no
information other than this e-mail message [980115004946 cited above about
any possible outbreak on Bougainville. If there are cases of communicable
leprosy (some cases have little or no risk of transmission to others,) then
there is risk of transmission to Solomon Islanders who come into contact
with these individuals when there is travel between Choiseul Province
(northern part of Solomons) and Bougainville. The immunization program is
not likely to have a significant effect on this risk of transmission. The
Solomon Islands leprosy control programme should be able to provide the
necessary information to Solomon Islanders and to deal with any cases which
may result. It is important to remember that the "usual" incubation period
for leprosy is at least 2 years.
--
